ugh a compelling analysis of its iconography and of the literary sources for the Umayyad period. It illuminates not only the way of life of the early Muslim elite but also the long afterglow of late antique Syria.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArabic poetryy622-750xHistory and criticism. 0aMural painting and decoration, UmayyadzJordanxForeign influences. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aabbasid.  aabd al malik.  aal azraq.  aal buldn.  aalois musil.  aamir.  aancient art.  aapodyterium.  aarab.  aarabic poetry.  aarabic.  aarchitecture.  aart history.  abath house.  abaths.  acaptive woman.  acourt life.  adancing girls.  adecorative arts.  adesert.  adynasty.  afemininity.  afrescoes.  agender.  ahunt.  ahunting lodge.  aiconography.  airan.  aislam.  ajordan.  akhusraw.  alate antiquity.  amiddle east.  amonument.  amurals.  amusicians.  amuslim.  amythology.  anegus.  anonfiction.  aode.  apersia.  aprince.  aprincess.  aqusayr amra.  aroderic.  aroyal court.  aself fashioning.  ashaykh musa.  asyria.  aumayyad.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023665340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092960940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929609423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929609/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY